column2: Do not drive a car today
Do not use a straw today
column19:
For instance, have you ever thought about the meaning of a straw? Every 
cold beverage that you get served - Shush, you beer addicts… - comes 
with a straw. And conditioned to its usage, we stick it in there without
 thinking.
column20:
Some habits and behavioural patterns are so strong that we are not even 
conscious about them. It is like a Meerkat that never drinks water, 
because it gets his need for water satisfies by eating succulents 
(plants that are full of liquids). But in contrast to this pattern, 
which is beneficial to the Meerkat, the luxury of civilisation has 
shaped certain patterns that are not exactly beneficial to us.

Straight Sitting
column6: Pay attention to the way you sit and walk during the whole day/week. Sit up and walk with a straight back, shoulders low in your back and a proud and straight neck. Sitting behind a desk all day is no excuse for harming your body by taking a bad position.

column2: Etymology
column6: Think of a word you really like. Look up where it comes from in your own language, and learn it by heart in 5 different languages. If you have the time (and interest), look up where it comes from in these other languages too, and reflect on the differences/similarities between all 6 languages/origins.

column2: Highlight Moments
column6: Think of the best moment you’ve experienced in the last 30 days. Take the time to relive this moment and enjoy the feeling. If you feel like you didn’t have a ‘best moment’ in these days, then reflect on this period and try to separate your ‘feelings’ from ‘what happened’. Maybe after all, a lot of nice things happened without you noticing?

column2: Being oneself only
column6: Spend one full hour just ‘being’. Turn off your phone, go for a walk around town/ in nature (or if the weather is shitty, take public transport or go to a local café) on your own. Try to avoid places where you’ll encounter somebody you already know. Contact with strangers is allowed. Don’t read, don’t watch a movie. Just be.

column2: Book Club Chat
column6: Reading time! Go to a bookstore, look around and ask a person that looks interesting to you what hir favorite book is. If you cannot find somebody that suits you, go to other bookstores or libraries. Lend the book from a library, try to buy it second hand or read it on your e-reader. Read at least the first chapter of the book- even if it doesn’t sound interesting to you.

column2: Urban Exploration
column6: Go to a neighborhood in your town where you have never been, or that you rarely visit, and that is preferably very different from where you live. Try to imagine what the life of people who live here must be like: who are the people who you see on the streets? How do the buildings look? Do people look happy?

column2: Memories
column6: Try to remember what you were like/your life was like in highschool. What did you expect from life back then, and where are you know? How do you feel about this? What do you want to do with this feeling?

column2: Family Reflection
column6: Think of you closest family members and try to see every one of them as an individual person (so for example, not as a mother, but as a person). What are their weaknesses? What do you appreciate about them? What does it mean to you to be related to them as family members?

Eat on your own, in complete silence (as far as is possible) and actively enjoy every bite of your meal. Take at least half an hour for this (this means, sitting at the table for half an hour with only your meal as a companion).

column2: Small scale fasting (on weekend days?).
column6: Try ‘listening’ to your body: only eat when you are hungry, and not if you only ‘feel like’ eating something, or because it’s ‘lunchtime’. (Maybe a problem for people who have a tendency to become anorexique etc.?)
